Generating a frame

Frame Formation

We start with a stump of data, it might be a web request - and the next step would be we create a segment , which would be your TCP/UDP Header (Segment Port Address)
Within that address, we have the source and destination Port address
The next part of encapsulation is adding the IP Header, at the network layer , it is called a packet.
Within that, we have a source and destination IP address
The last part of this frame formation is the frame header.
Within that, we have a MAC Address
and with a frame, not only is there a header, we also have a trailer. That is the frame check sequence
This is to provide error detection on a network by creating a cyclic redundancy check value that the network will check while travelling along its way


All the way on the top, is of course your frame header - , Frame is Ethernet - II and you see the source and destination MAC addresses within that frame header
Next represents the network layer in form of packet - IPV4
Transport Layer - Segment - TCP, SRC PORT, DAT PORT , SEQ , ACK , LEN
A web request - Data - HTTP
